Telecom Customer Churn analysis Using Logistic Regression, Naive Bayes and KNN Classifiers¶

  • Rahul Sharma (Ogre) (Author, All Rights Reserved)

DOMAIN: Telecom¶

DATA DESCRIPTION:¶

The data set includes information about:

  • Customers who left within the last month – Churn (target)
  • Services that each customer has signed up for – phone, multiple lines, internet, online security, online backup, device protection, tech support, and streaming TV and movies
  • Customer account information – how long they've been a customer, contract, payment method, paperless billing, monthly charges, and total charges
  • Demographic info about customers – gender, age range, and if they have partners and dependents

PROJECT OBJECTIVE:¶

Build a model that will help to identify the potential customers who have a higher probability to churn. This helps the company to understand the patterns of customer churn and will increase the focus on strategizing customer retention.

Data Dictionary¶

  • CustomerID: Passenger Identity
  • Gender: Whether the customer is a male or a female
  • SeniorCitizen: Whether the customer is a senior citizen or not (1, 0)
  • Partner: Whether the customer has a partner or not (Yes, No)
  • Dependents: Whether the customer has dependents or not (Yes, No)
  • Tenure: Number of months the customer has stayed with the company
  • PhoneService: Whether the customer has a phone service or not (Yes, No)
  • MultipleLines: Whether the customer has multiple lines or not (Yes, No, No phone service)
  • InternetService: Customer’s internet service provider (DSL, Fiber optic, No)
  • OnlineSecurity: Whether the customer has online security or not (Yes, No, No internet service)
  • OnlineBackup: Whether the customer has online backup or not (Yes, No, No internet service)
  • DeviceProtection: Whether the customer has device protection or not (Yes, No, No internet service)
  • TechSupport: Whether the customer has tech support or not (Yes, No, No internet service)
  • StreamingTV: Whether the customer has streaming TV or not (Yes, No, No internet service)
  • StreamingMovies: Whether the customer has streaming movies or not (Yes, No, No internet service)
  • Contract: The contract term of the customer (Month-to-month, One year, Two year)
  • PaperlessBilling: Whether the customer has paperless billing or not (Yes, No)
  • PaymentMethod: The customer’s payment method (Electronic check, Mailed check Bank transfer (automatic), Credit card (automatic))
  • MonthlyCharges: The amount charged to the customer monthly
  • TotalCharges: The total amount charged to the customer
  • Churn: Whether the customer churned or not (Yes or No)

# try and except is important to use while making a connection with a database
# my_conf.txt file contained in the same folder as this notebook has the details to the server connection. 
# we can save the details as dictionary as well. but such sensitive data should be well masked.

try:
    connection = sql_py.connect(option_files='my_conf.txt', option_groups=['connection_details'])
    if connection.is_connected():
        db_Info = connection.get_server_info()
        print("Connected to MySQL Server version ", db_Info)
        cursor = connection.cursor() #creating the cursor object for the connection
        cursor.execute("select database();")
        record = cursor.fetchone()
        print("Connected to databases:", record)
except sql_py.Error as err:
    if err.errno == errorcode.ER_ACCESS_DENIED_ERROR:
        print("Something is wrong with the user name or password")
    elif err.errno == errorcode.ER_BAD_DB_ERROR:
        print("Database does not exist")
    else:
        print(err)

#defining a function
def ifDuplicateSamples(data):
  NoOfDuplicateRows = data.duplicated().sum()
  if NoOfDuplicateRows == 0:
    print("There are no duplicate rows")
    return
  else:
    print("There are ",NoOfDuplicateRows,"duplicate rows")

# Function to describe a continuous feature
def num_uni_analysis(data,feature):
    variable = data[feature]
    sns.displot(x=variable,kde=True) 
    plt.title(f"Distribution Plot of {feature}")
    plt.axvline(variable.mean(), color='red')
    plt.axvline(variable.median(), color='green')
    plt.show()
    print("----------------------")
    print("Skewness is: ", round(variable.skew(),4),"\n")
    print("Five point summary is: \n", variable.describe())

In [25]:
def compute_vif(data, numeric_features):
    X = data[numeric_features]
    vif = pd.DataFrame()
    vif["Variable"] = X.columns
    vif["VIF"] = [variance_inflation_factor(X.values, i) for i in range(X.shape[1])]
    return vif

In [43]:
def chi_2_test(data,feature1,feature2):
    ct = pd.crosstab(data[feature],data[feature2])
    c, p, dof, expected = chi2_contingency(ct)

    if p < 0.05:
        print(f"{p} is less than 0.05.")
        print(f"We reject the null hypothesis that the features are independent of each other.\n")
        print(f"So, {feature1} and {feature2}- NOT INDEPENDENT")
        if feature2 == 'Churn':
            print(f"Thus {feature1} is a feature of statistical importance.")
    else:
        print(f"{p} is greater than 0.05.")
        print(f"We fail to reject the null hypothesis that the features are independent of each other.\n")
        print(f"So {feature1} and {feature2}- INDEPENDENT")
        if feature2 == 'Churn':
            print(f"So we can drop {feature1} from our dataset.")

Observations:¶

  • Fair distribution of gender across the dataset. The company attacts both major genders of population.
  • In 'SeniorCitizen', we take for granted thar 1 means that the customer is a Senior Citizen. And 0 means that the customer is not. Most of them are not Senior Citizens. Senior Citizens do not like to subscribe too much to this company.
  • Almost half of the customers have partners, and half don't. Pertains to common sense.
  • Almost 2/3rds of the customers don't have dependents. Pertains to common sense.
  • Over 90% of the customers use PhoneService. Pertains to common sense. 9.7 percent of them might here only for Internet services. This fact is significant because it might turn out that 'PhoneService' may not be a feature of importance.
  • The above data is contained in the feature 'Multiple Lines'. So we can remove 'PhoneService'. But we will confirm with a chi-2 test before going ahead.
  • 21.7% of the sample population do not avail Internet Service. This figure is repeated in all those feature which correspond to InternetService being availed, i.e. OnlineSecurity, OnlineBackup, DeviceProtection, TechSupport, StreamingTV, StreamingMovies. Thus the data is consistent.
  • 38.8 percent of customer use StreamingMovies service and 38.4 percent use StreamingTV. These seems to be some correlation between these two features. We will check.
  • More than fifty percent of the customers prefer to have a month-to-month plan.
  • More than fifty percent of the customers prefer paperless billing. Maybe the data is old. I would expect most of today's customers to prefer Paperless Billing
  • There are four ways of paying bill. Almost all of them seem to see similar preference from the customers.

  • Over 70 percent of the values are 0/No.
  • The dataset we have is highly imbalanced in favor of No. Thus the recall for No would be very low.
  • I do not wish to change the threshold ROC for every model. That would be painstaking, and most important using different thresholds for different models does not seem like a good idea to me.
  • Instead, I am going to use artificial sampling with SMOTE-ENN resampling that uses KNN algorithm to create new date points for each synthetic sample, and deletes the misclassified synthetic samples using the same KNN. One can check its description and logic here: https://towardsdatascience.com/imbalanced-classification-in-python-smote-enn-method-db5db06b8d50

In [61]:
# First defining a function which evalutes a Classfier model

def EvaluateClassifier(Y_test,y_hat):
  print("----------------------------------------------------------------------\n")
  cf_matrix = confusion_matrix(Y_test, y_hat)
  names = ['TN','FP','FN','TP']
  counts = ['{0:0.0f}'.format(value) for value in cf_matrix.flatten()]
  percentages = ['{0:.2%}'.format(value) for value in cf_matrix.flatten()/np.sum(cf_matrix)]
  labels = [f'{v1}\n{v2}\n{v3}' for v1, v2, v3 in zip(names,counts,percentages)]
  labels = np.asarray(labels).reshape(2,2)
  sns.heatmap(cf_matrix, annot=labels, fmt='', cmap='Wistia')
  plt.title("Confusion Matrix")  
  plt.show()

  
  print("\n----------------------------------------------------------------------\n")
  print("Classification Report")
  print(classification_report(Y_test,y_hat))

  print("\n----------------------------------------------------------------------\n")
  fpr, tpr, thresholds = roc_curve(Y_test, y_hat)
  plt.plot(fpr, tpr)
  # set limits for x and y axes
  plt.xlim([0.0, 1.0])
  plt.ylim([0.0, 1.0])
  # plot the straight line showing worst prediction for the model
  plt.plot([0, 1], [0, 1],'r--')
  
  plt.title('AUC-ROC curve')
  plt.xlabel('FPR (1-Specificity)')
  plt.ylabel('TPR (Sensitivity)')
  plt.text(x = 0.02, y = 0.9, s = ('AUC Score:', round(roc_auc_score(Y_test, y_hat),3)))
  plt.show()
  print("\n----------------------------------------------------------------------")
In [62]:
# DEFINING A FUNCTION WHICH DISPLAYS TRAIN AND TEST ACCURACY
def train_test_accuracy(classifier):
    y_pred_train = classifier.predict(X_train)
    y_pred_test = classifier.predict(X_test)
    train_accuracy = accuracy_score(Y_train,y_pred_train)
    test_accuracy = accuracy_score(Y_test,y_pred_test)
    print(f"For {classifier}:")
    print(f"Train accuracy is {train_accuracy}, and\nTest accuracy is {test_accuracy}")
    return

  • Too many categorial features spoil the game for Logistic Regression, because it is an example of generalized linear models which use linear combinations of the predictor features to create a sigmoid shaped classifier. Categorical features are sparsely populated in feature space as compared to continuous, and contribute to the linear models with low parametric values.
  • Also there is a clear homoscadiscticity in the features space in addition to highy skewness and linear feature dependence.
  • Thus the accuracy and F scores is low.
  • We can use optimization methods like gradient descent and even PCA to better the classifier, but that is not expected of this project.
  • The train and test accuracy is almost same indicating a model well suited to generalization.

  • Even with the default K=5, the model is working well and is the best of the three we have chosen to analyze.
  • It is simply because the algorithm is instance based and non-parametric.
  • In KNN, the choice of k is very critical. A small value of k means that noise will have a higher influence on the result. A large value makes it computationally expensive and is contradictory to the basic idea behind KNN, that close points might have similar densities or classes.
  • We need to create an 'Error_Rate vs K' plot. And choose the K with minimum Error Rate.
In [68]:
def KvsErrorRatePLOT():
  error_rate = []
  for i in range(1,30):
    knn = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=i)
    knn.fit(X_train,Y_train)
    yi_cap = knn.predict(X_test)
    error_rate.append(np.mean(yi_cap != Y_test))
    
  plt.figure(figsize=(10,6))
  plt.plot(range(1,30),error_rate,color='Green', linestyle='dashed',\
             marker='X', markerfacecolor='Red', markersize=7)
  plt.title('Error Rate vs. K')
  plt.xlabel('K value')
  plt.ylabel('Error Rate')
  plt.show()
In [69]:
KvsErrorRatePLOT()
  • K=3 would be most optimal, as the error rate is minimum.
  • Lower values of K will lead to overfitting
  • Let us implement with KNN model with K=3

5. Conclusion and improvisation¶

  1. In this project, we imported two files in MySQL server, warehoused it, and the imported it into our python notebook with mysql connector.
  2. The two files were merged into one and saved as a single DataFrame for further processing with modules like Pandas.
  3. The data had 7043 samples, 20 predictor features and 1 predicted feature (Churn).
  4. We approached the dataset conservatively, employing a wide range of EDA methods from Univariate to Bivariate like visualization, chi-square and Kruskal Wallis test, and came to the conclusion that 4 features could be removed.
  5. Then, the Outcome was analyzed. It was highly biased towards Churn=NO. So we employed an optimum resampling technique (SMOTE-ENN) and descreased the number of samples to 6124.
  6. Now the dataset was split in 70:30 ratio after properly scaling it with MinMax Scaler, and fed into three ML algorithms chosen.
  7. The results were encouraging and as per the expectations.
  8. KNN with K=3 gave the best result (accuracy, F score, and AUC score = 0.97), and we chose it to further improve it for industrial applications.
